Remembering the very American ideal that labor rights - they are human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have offered legislation that the organization of trade unions is protected as a civil right.
"Where are the trade unions, there are and the jobs of the middle class," said Ellison, a Democrat from Minnesota, who is co-chairman of the Congress of the Progressive Faction.
That is why I am proud to represent the act of expanding the rights of workers, together with the symbol of the civil rights movement by John Lewis.
This innovative bill would give workers the same legal possibilities for discrimination against trade union organizations, which in other forms of discrimination, stopping force opponents of trade unions
Amendment of regulation of labor relations in such a way as to allow workers who face discrimination for their participation in trade union organizations, to seek justice in civilian courts - and to receive compensation for damages and punitive damages - reasonable and necessary initiative.
However, this is certainly not a radical initiative - at least by American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand is that the offer Allison Lewis et al bills - remember very American idea.
Despite the attacks, which the unions have been in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the nation - Americans once supported the country all over the world to take expand and respect labor rights.
There was a time that is still remembered by millions of Americans, at a time when this country is to defend democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to organize.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his aides helped the country to adopt a constitution drawn up so as to ensure that Hideki Tojo militarized autocracy was replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that workers and their trade unions play a role in the formation of a new Japan, they have included a text that explicitly recognize that "the right of workers to organize and to negotiate and to take collective action is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his aides helped the Germans to write a constitution that guaranteed that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
Recognizing that workers will have to organize themselves and to be heard in the new state, the Germans included an article that openly stated: "The right to form associations in order to protect and improve working and economic conditions is guaranteed to everyone and to each profession or field of activity.
Agreements that restrict or seek to undermine this right will have no legal force; measures for these purposes will be considered illegal.
When the former first lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Commission on Human Rights, which was the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which in 1948 will be adopted by the United Nations as a global agreement, Roosevelt and the drafters included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to organize and join trade unions for the protection of his interests. "
Generations of Americans have taken for granted the basic position that the labor rights - they are human rights.
When this country is consulted others on how to create a civil and democratic society, Americans were told that the right to organize trade unions - and the fact that the union was involved as an equal partner in collective bargaining with corporations and government agencies - should be protected.
Now, when these rights are under attack in America, it is wise, indeed, go back to the American ideal that working people should have the right to organize and to have their voices heard in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said, fifty years ago:
History - a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the trade union movement does not undermine the strength of the nation, but increased them.
Raising the living standards of millions, labor miraculously created a market for the industry and the whole nation rose to an unimaginable level of production.
Those who attack the unions, forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History remembers how should we.
Official recognition of labor rights as human rights - and the expansion of civil rights, to prevent discrimination against trade union organizations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis revive the ideals that America has historically expanded and made a promise of democracy a reality.
