SPRING prepared cold surprise in the south of South Australia, bringing heavy rains and strong winds that affected the flights to Adelaide airport.
Another 5 mm of rain fell on the city in the evening at 9 pm, followed by 6.6 mm, which fell on Sunday night.
The latter was preceded by two short rain showers with gusty winds, including a storm that nachalalas shortly before 8 pm and poured nearly 4 mm in about 10 minutes.
After the winter was an early portion of the spring last week, the temperature dropped again on Monday to a maximum of just 15,8C in the city.
Squally conditions are supposed to have served as one of the reasons for the delay planting Virgin Airlines flight from Melbourne to Adelaide.
The plane was scheduled to land just after 7:30 pm, but was in the area of ​​wind shear - a sudden change in wind speed or direction over a short distance - and was forced to climb.
Wind gusts reached 50 km / h on the ground at the airport of Adelaide at this time.
Flight data showed that the aircraft had to climb during the second landing, and the plane eventually landed around 8:40 pm.
The delay of the flight caused the subsequent delay of several other flights, including flights from Dubai Emirates and Qantas flight from Sydney.
Maximum 16C projected in Adelaide on Tuesday, with a probability of one or two showers.
