Israeli children return to school after the war in Gaza
Thousands of Israeli children in areas near the Gaza Strip again went to school on Monday after having spent the summer in bomb shelters when rockets and mines rain down on their villages during the 50-day war between Israel and Hamas, while schools in the Gaza Strip remained closed while being rebuilt area after the fighting.
Start of school brought a sense of joy and excitement hit by rockets settlements of southern Israel, but traces of the fighting remained fresh.
In the southern city of Ashdod kindergarten staff "Pashosh", which hit a rocket fragments removed traces of the walls and children's slides before the arrival of students.
"We're a little afraid, but gladly look into the future," said Ronit Bart, a resident of Kibbutz Sa'ad and English teacher at his school.
Many children in our area really needs to get back to regular life.
Her 11-year-old daughter, Shani Barth said that suddenly start going back to school "a little strange".
"It was a difficult time, and we did not come out of their homes," she said.
President Reuven Rivlin visited the kibbutz, which is located near the border with Gaza, to express their support.
Before the cease-fire halted the war last week, thousands of residents of border villages such as Saad, do not go outside or have left their homes, fleeing to safer areas further from the Gaza Strip in order to escape from the rocket and mortar fire.
Many people in Nahal Oz settlement near the border with Gaza, where Palestinian splinter mine was killed 4-year-old boy, doubt, that they should go back.
The Ministry of Education reported that about a dozen families have not returned.
Their children were sent to other schools at this time.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu visited a school in Sderot, a town on the border with Gaza, which is badly affected by Palestinian fire.
He advised the children to carefully study and said, "We will do everything possible to give you the knowledge and to ensure your safety."
Israel and Hamas agreed to an indefinite cease-fire last Tuesday.
The ceasefire immediately put an end to the fighting, but remained unresolved key issues such as requiring Hamas to lift the Egyptian-Israeli blockade of Gaza and the opening of airports and sea ports in Gaza.
Israel wants Hamas to lay down arms and returned the bodies of two Israeli soldiers killed in the war.
It is expected that a new stage of indirect talks will begin later this month in Egypt.
The war killed more than 2,100 Palestinians, including three-quarters were civilians, and at least 494 of the Child, it is estimated the Palestinian side and the UN.
Israel disputes those figures and says that at least half of those killed were militants; Despite this, he has not provided any substantial evidence to support this assertion.
On the Israeli side lost 66 soldiers and six civilians, including a Thai worker.
During the fighting, Hamas and other militants in Gaza fired unit 4591 rockets and mortars at Israeli towns, mainly in the south.
The Israeli army, meanwhile, has conducted more than 5,000 aircraft and other attacks.
As a result of the Israeli attacks were damaged and destroyed thousands of homes in the Gaza Strip, and an estimated 250,000 people have taken refuge in more than 100 schools that have been transformed into shelters.
Due to the fact that tens of thousands of people were still in shelters, and the fighting continued, the officials in charge of education, last week postponed the start of the school year.
"I hope that the school will soon be opened, so we were able to complete our education, the children of the world and Jewish children," said Mohammed Amara, 13-year-old boy, who now lives in one of the schools in Gaza.
According to popular criterion property prices showed the greatest increase in winter in seven years.
The index of housing costs RP Data CoreLogic Hedonic for housing prices in the Australian capital increased by 1.1 percent in August, the RP data reported on Monday.
This increase resulted in a cumulative increase in June, July and August by 4.2 percent, to the largest increase during the winter months from 2007.
The annual price growth was 10.9 percent, more than double the growth in the 12 months to August 2013, but the increase was not evenly distributed across the country.
RP Data research director Tim Lawless said that Sydney and Melbourne are two-tiered market.
RP Data figures show that in Sydney house prices rose by 16.1 percent over the past year, while in Melbourne - by 11.7 percent.
The next power markets were Adelaide, Brisbane and Darwin, where prices rose by an average of five to six percent.
At the other end of the scale I was in Canberra, which was held by government spending cuts, where prices have risen by only 1.4 percent per year.
Mr Lawless said that now, when the spring, there will be a increase in the number of properties for sale in the next few months, it would be "a real challenge" for the market.
"Given the current high rate of auction sales, the overall high rate of sales and the current conditions of low interest rates is likely that house prices will rise further over the next three months," he said.
